(1)
Jefferson Market Courthouse and clock tower, with the excavation on the site of the old jail and the law and bail bond offices on the north side of 10th Street (formerly Amos Street), from
Greenwich Avenue to Sixth Avenue.
The courthouse, on the S.W. corner of Sixth Avenue and 10th Street, was erected in 1875. Prior to that there was a tall, roundish wooden tower, rather like a lighthouse in appearance, on the same site. The new House of Detention for Women is to be built in 1930-31, to fill the rest of the triangular block in which
the courthouse stands.
The break in the north side of 10th Street is the entrance to
Patchin Place, a semi-private residential court.
December 31, 1929
P.L. Sperr.
(2)
The same, showing only the N.E. corner at Greenwich Avenue and the south side to Sixth Avenue, three years later, with the new House of Detntion for Women on the site of the old jail.
March 6, 1933
P.L. Sperr.

10th Street, adjoining the N.E. end S.E. corners at Greenwich Avenue, the north side seen from and including the clearing on the south side, where the old jail has been demolished and the new House of Detention for Women is being constructed. As may be seen in this picture, one of the branches of Minetta Creek still runs underground in this neighborhood, and it is necessary to keep pumping out the water while foundations are being laid.
The building housing Cushman's Bakery is the corner building at Greenwich Avenue; it is the original Cushman bakery, which has occupied this building since 1854.

P. L. Sperr.

December 14, 1929.

Greenwich Ave, west side, north from and including the S.W. corner of 10th Street, to but not including Charles Street. This view also shows 10th Street, north side, from but not including Patchin Place, to and including Greenwich Ave, The excavation in the foreground is for the new municipal women's jail on the site of old Jefferson Market Courts.

December 14, 1929.

P. L. Sperr.

This branch of the Cushman chain is the original Cushman store, established in this building in 1854.
The car track in the foreground is the westbound track of the 8th Street crosstown surface line.

(1)
10th Street (formerly Amos Street), north side, at Greenwich Avenue, showing the Cushman Bakery at the N.E. corner of Greenwich Avenue, and old houses, remodelled into studio apartments, at and adjoining the N.W. corner. This particular Cushman store is of interest because it used to be the original Cushman Bakery before Cushman's became an incorporated chain, and has occupied that old brick building ever since 1854. March 29, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.
